  "read": "The current best TileLang compact-final branch is tb256/gps512/cap320, not tb64. It reduces the compact partial stream 4x, from 128 MiB to 32 MiB, and reduces VMEM write instructions 4x and waves 4x, but full latency improves only about 1.6 percent because total producer instruction count barely changes: tb256 still issues about 924.5M SQ instructions, including 318.7M LDS, 270.2M VALU, 95.7M SALU, 45.5M branch, and the same 41.9M BF16 MFMA instructions. The fold is solved: trace fold dispatch is about 0.006 ms and timed fold-only is sub-0.04 ms. The remaining wall is still the producer body: the large dynamic shared-memory accumulation table plus PairSlots/index/control work around the MFMA loop. The smaller 256-group panel experiment validates the intuition but rejects that simple lever; smaller LDS per CTA is outweighed by more panels and more padded selected chunks.",
  "decision": "retain_tb256_gps512_cap320_current_best; reject_gps256_cap192; next_work_rewrite_producer_not_fold",
  "next_kernel_targets": [
    "Do not spend more time on final fold/scatter; upside is below 0.05 ms.",
    "A simple smaller panel is not enough. Need a producer layout that reduces LDS/index work without increasing panel count or selected chunks.",
    "Investigate register or wave-local segmented accumulation for hot subset rows, or fuse compressor/LI dKV consumption so the producer avoids the dense 512x64 FP32 table.",
    "If staying in TileLang, inspect generated source and try reducing PairSlots double-load/control paths before changing the route panel geometry again."
  ]
